They’ve cracked the code to making campaigns that are not just memorable, but viral-worthy. From dreamy ski cabin shoots to mesmerizing supermodel moments, Jacquemus knows how to pull us into a fantasy. 

But here’s the real story—Jacquemus wasn’t always the powerhouse it is today. Simon Porte Jacquemus started at 19 with no flashy budgets or big investors, relying on friends, local spaces, and pure creativity to bring his vision to life. 

And reason #4?
Jacquemus’ use of supermodels is pure genius. Supermodels bring global attention, instant credibility, and aspiration, making campaigns unforgettable. Paired with surreal settings—like a red balloon dress in a field—they create bold, viral moments.

Why it works:

Global Reach: Supermodels’ massive fanbases amplify campaigns.

Aspirational Appeal: They make the brand feel premium and desirable.

Media Buzz: Stunning visuals + supermodels = endless conversation.

Iconic Impact: These campaigns become timeless art, keeping Jacquemus in the spotlight.

It’s not just marketing—it’s cultural storytelling.

#Jacquemus #FashionMarketing #DreamsToReality"

I could’ve just captioned this carousel with:
“Life’s been pretty exciting lately 👀💫🙏🤍”

But let me tell you a little story instead —

Last year was far from easy.
When I decided to move to Mumbai, I was standing at one of the lowest points of my life. I was scared, unsure, but somewhere deep down I knew — this was necessary. Necessary to turn the page, necessary to figure out what the next chapter looks like.

Honestly, this has always been my way of growing — by stepping into the unknown, into challenges that force me to stretch, to stumble, to fall… and eventually to rise again.

I’m not someone who usually sits and cries about what went wrong for months on end— but this time, I also want to say this out loud:
I am proud of myself.
For the stumbles, for the courage, for every small step that brought me here. 🤍

And now — things have slowly started to make a little more sense.
I am deeply grateful for every single opportunity that’s coming my way — but I also know that it’s not just coming to me. I’m working for it. I’m moving towards it. I’m showing up for it and fighting small battles every single day.

Excited to see what’s ahead ✨

Here is a bit about the collection :
Pondicherry is a collection of easy, everyday pieces that feel just as good on a weekend away as they do on a weekday in the city. Think soft handloom cottons, wispy organzas, breezy chanderis, and linen that breathes with you. The silhouettes are relaxed but thoughtful - long gathered dresses, fluid kurtas, checked sarees, printed co-ord sets — made to be worn and reworn.

There’s a playfulness in the palette: bright yellows, deep rusts, calming greens and checks that nod to old Madras textiles. You’ll find floral block prints from Sanganer, handmade details like wooden or glass beads, and fabrics woven in Bengal — pieces that carry craft but feel light, modern, and quietly nostalgic.

latestPosts.caption:
New beginnings come with boxes… and a whole lot of decisions.
I recently moved into a new studio space — a blank canvas that I’ve been building up, piece by piece.

From the very start, I made myself a quiet little promise:
Nothing comes into this space unless it means something.
Not just pretty decor, but things that hold purpose, spark joy, or tell a story.

So somewhere between scrolling for inspiration and sipping on late-night chai,
I came across a brand called @fig.living

Aesthetic? Check. Functional? Double check.
Assembly? …Well. 😅

Let’s just say the manual said “easy setup,”
but my brain decided to turn it into a puzzle challenge.
Screwed in the wrong side, flipped the base twice —
classic Aahna.

But when it finally came together…
the energy of the whole room shifted.
It felt right.

That’s what this studio is slowly becoming —
Not a styled set, but a space full of meaning.
Of little pieces that belong.

Welcome home, fig lamp. ✨🍃
